{"title": "Black and White Magic", "content": "Okay, you're designing an RPG, and you've got your Fighter, Mage, Thief, but something's missing. The magic adds a lot of strategic elements to the combat system, and you don't want to have just one magic user. You want to add more variety. But you can't just create a copy of the mage; it has to be different somehow. So how to make the two mages distinct? Simple. Have one attack and the other heal!\n\nBlack and White Magic is a common way of having more than one magician character or class while having them remain distinct. One of the mages specializes in offensive magic which causes damage, negative status, or otherwise harms the enemy, while the other specializes in defensive magic to cure their allies, remove negative status, or increase their own stats. They are often referred to as \"wizard\" and \"cleric\" (or some variation) respectively.\n\nNot to be confused with Black Magic and White Magic, which are distinct tropes and don't usually overlap with this. If a character can do both, then he's The Red Mage. Characters who use black magic are Black Mages, characters who use white magic are White Mages.", "url": "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/BlackAndWhiteMagic", "media_links": ["/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/FinalFantasyTacticsA2", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/PerfectWorld", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/DCUniverseOnline", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/FinalFantasyXIV", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/OgreBattle", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/WarCraftII", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/WarcraftIII", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/WorldOfWarcraft", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/FinalFantasy", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/DragonQuest", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/UltimaIII", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/FireEmblem", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/FireEmblemThreeHouses", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/FireEmblemGaiden", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/SecretOfMana", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/TrialsOfMana", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/BahamutLagoon", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Franchise/FinalFantasy", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/ChronoTrigger", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/MightAndMagic", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/MightAndMagic", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/DungeonSiege", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/Avernum", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/MasterOfTheMonsterLair", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Manga/DeliciousInDungeon", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Literature/LoneWolf", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Literature/VillainsByNecessity", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Literature/TheDarkProfitSaga", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/TabletopGame/DungeonsAndDragons", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Franchise/FinalFantasy", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/TabletopGame/Ironclaw"], "non_media_links": ["/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/JobSystem", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/BlackMage", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/WhiteMage", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/FighterMageThief", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/SuperheroSpeciation", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/SquishyWizard", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/TheMedic", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/BlackMagic", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/WhiteMagic", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/TheRedMage", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/BlackMage", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/WhiteMage", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/BlackMagic", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/WhiteMagic", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/KarmaMeter", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/KarmaMeter", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/AntiMagic", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/BlackMagic", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/TropeNamer", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/SummonMagic", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/StatusEffect", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/UselessUsefulSpell", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/TheRedMage", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/LightEmUp", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/AnAxeToGrind", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/JobSystem", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/LifeDrain", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/GameplayAndStorySegregation", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/WhiteMage", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/BlackMage", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/NamesToRunAwayFromReallyFast", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/ExactlyWhatItS